<doc id="313577" wikidata="Q3805544" url="?curid=313577" title="Jack Belrose">
<text>John Skelton Belrose (24 November 1926 – 19 September 2024) was a Canadian radio scientist.

==Life and career==
Belrose was born in the small town of Warner, Alberta on 24 November 1926. He attended the University of Cambridge, where he was awarded a PhD in 1958. He worked for the Defence Research Telecommunications Establishment (DRTE) for 33 years. He was a member of the Canadian Amateur Radio Hall of Fame and, along with Walter Cronkite, was awarded the Radio Club of America&#x27;s Armstrong Medal on 16 November 2007. Belrose died on 19 September 2024, at the age of 97.

==References==
==External links==
*Remembrances of a Radio Scientist - Belrose&#x27;s report on his 50th anniversary of working in the field of radio science.
*The Sounds of a Spark Transmitter Telegraphy and Telephony - a paper by Jack Belrose.
